[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] In computer programming, **duck typing** is an application of the duck test—"If it walks like a duck and it quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck"—to determine whether an object can be used for a particular purpose.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] With nominative typing, an object is of a given type if it is declared as such (or if a type's association with the object is inferred through mechanisms such as object inheritance).
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] With duck typing, an object is of a given type if it has all methods and properties required by that type.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] Duck typing may be viewed as a usage-based structural equivalence between a given object and the requirements of a type.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] In some statically typed languages such as Boo and D, class type checking can be specified to occur at runtime rather than at compile time.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] C# can invoke dynamic typing which behaves similar to duck typing, through the keyword `dynamic`.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] Duck typing is similar to, but distinct from, structural typing.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] Structural typing is a static typing system that determines type compatibility and equivalence by a type's structure, whereas duck typing is dynamic and determines type compatibility by only that part of a type's structure that is accessed during runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] The TypeScript, Elm and Python languages support structural typing to varying degrees.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] Protocols and interfaces provide a way to explicitly declare that some methods, operators or behaviors must be defined.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] If a third-party library implements a class that cannot be modified, a client cannot use an instance of it with an interface unknown to that library even if the class satisfies the interface requirements.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] A common solution to this problem is the adapter pattern.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] In contrast, with duck typing, the object would be accepted directly without the need for an adapter.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] Template (also called generic) functions or methods apply the duck test in a static typing context; this brings all of the advantages and disadvantages of static versus dynamic type checking.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] Duck typing can also be more flexible in that only the methods actually called at runtime must be implemented, while templates require implementations of all methods that cannot be proven unreachable at compile time.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] In languages such as Java, Scala and Objective-C, reflection may be employed to inspect whether objects implement methods or add necessary methods at runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/duck-typing] For example, Java's MethodHandle API can be used in this manner.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] A **dynamic programming language** is a type of programming language that allows various operations to be determined and executed at runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This is different from the compilation phase.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Key decisions about variables, method calls, or data types are made when the program is running, unlike in static languages, where the structure and types are fixed during compilation.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This allows developers to write more adaptable and concise code.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] For instance, in a dynamic language, a variable can start as an integer.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] It can later be reassigned to hold a string without explicit type declarations.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This feature of dynamic typing enables more fluid and less restrictive coding.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Developers can focus on the logic and functionality rather than the constraints of the language.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Some dynamic languages offer an *eval* function.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This function takes a string or abstract syntax tree containing code in the language and executes it.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] If this code stands for an expression, the resulting value is returned.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Erik Meijer and Peter Drayton distinguish the runtime code generation offered by eval from the dynamic loading offered by shared libraries and warn that in many cases eval is used merely to implement higher-order functions (by passing functions as strings) or deserialization.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] A type or object system can typically be modified during runtime in a dynamic language.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This can mean generating new objects from a runtime definition or based on mixins of existing types or objects.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This can also refer to changing the inheritance or type tree, and thus altering the way that existing types behave (especially with respect to the invocation of methods).
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] As a lot of dynamic languages come with a dynamic type system, runtime inference of types based on values for internal interpretation marks a common task.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] As value types may change throughout interpretation, it is regularly used upon performing atomic operations.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Static programming languages (possibly indirectly) require developers to define the size of utilized memory before compilation (unless working around with pointer logic).
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Consistent with object runtime alteration, dynamic languages implicitly need to (re-)allocate memory based on program individual operations.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Reflective programming (reflection) is common in many dynamic languages, and typically involves analysis of the types and metadata of generic or polymorphic data.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] However, it can also include full evaluation and modification of a program's code as data, as in the features that Lisp provides in analyzing S-expressions.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] A limited number of dynamic programming languages provide features which combine code introspection (the ability to examine classes, functions, and keywords to know what they are, what they do and what they know) and eval in a feature called macros.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Most programmers today who are aware of the term *macro* have encountered them in C or C++, where they are a static feature which is built in a small subset of the language, and are capable only of string substitutions on the text of the program.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] In dynamic languages, however, they provide access to the inner workings of the compiler, *and* full access to the interpreter, virtual machine, or runtime, allowing the definition of language-like constructs which can optimize code or modify the syntax or grammar of the language.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Assembly, C, C++, early Java, and Fortran do not generally fit into this category.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] The earliest dynamic programming language is considered to be Lisp (McCarthy, 1965) which continued to influence the design of programming languages to the present day.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] The following examples show dynamic features using the language Common Lisp and its Common Lisp Object System (CLOS).
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] This example shows how an existing instance can be changed to include a new slot when its class changes and that an existing method can be replaced with a new version.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] In the next example, the class **person** gets a new superclass.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] The **print** method gets redefined such that it assembles several methods into the effective method.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] The effective method gets assembled based on the class of the argument and the at runtime available and applicable methods.
[src:gradual-typing/dynamic-programming-language] Popular dynamic programming languages include JavaScript, Python, Ruby, PHP, Lua, and Perl.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] In many cases gradual typing is added to an existing dynamic language, creating a derived language *allowing* for, but not *requiring*, static typing to be used.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] In some cases, a language uses gradual typing from the start.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] However, there are performance and implementation complexity tradeoffs compared to dynamic or optional typing.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The term was coined by Jeremy Siek, who developed gradual typing in 2006 with Walid Taha.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] In gradual typing, a special type named *dynamic* is used to represent statically-unknown types.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The notion of type equality is replaced by a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The consistency relation is reflexive and symmetric but not transitive.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Prior attempts at integrating static and dynamic typing tried to make the dynamic type be both the top and bottom of the subtype hierarchy.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] However, because subtyping is transitive, that results in every type becoming related to every other type, and so subtyping would no longer rule out any static type errors.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The addition of a second phase of plausibility checking to the type system did not completely solve this problem.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Gradual typing can easily be integrated into the type system of an object-oriented language that already uses the subsumption rule to allow implicit upcasts with respect to subtyping.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The main idea is that consistency and subtyping are orthogonal ideas that compose nicely.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] To add subtyping to a gradually-typed language, simply add the subsumption rule and add a subtyping rule that makes the dynamic type a subtype of itself, because subtyping is supposed to be reflexive.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Gradual and optional typing are similar in that variables and expressions may be given types and the correctness of the typing is checked at compile time (which is *static typing*).
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] However, in a gradual type system, runtime checks are inserted at the boundaries of typed and untyped code.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] In an optional type system, all types are erased at compile time and untyped values can propagate through code that had type annotations.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] In a gradually typed language, an exception would be raised anytime a non-integer value is supplied for `credit` and stack traces would stop at invalid calls (`new Account("2")`).
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] `compare` functions as normal, illustrating how a program running in production could create and manipulate invalid `Accounts` without triggering an error.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] This could result in data corruption if the invalid instances are saved to a datastore.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Note however, that stack traces won't trace to the offending call but the setter.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] If the programmer forgets to pass externally provided values through the setter, it's still possible that an invalid instance could be created and saved to disk but discovered during a later execution.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] This makes data corruption harder to prevent and impedes tracking down offending code paths.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Examples of gradually typed languages derived from existing dynamically typed languages include Closure Compiler, Hack (for PHP), PHP (since 7.0), Typed Racket (for Racket), Typed Clojure (for Clojure), or cperl (a typed Perl 5).
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] ActionScript was a gradually typed language that interoperated with ECMAScript, though it originally arose separately as a sibling, both influenced by Apple's HyperTalk.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] A system for the J programming language has been developed, adding coercion, error propagation and filtering to the normal validation properties of the type system as well as applying type functions outside of function definitions, thereby the increasing flexibility of type definitions.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Conversely, C# started as a statically typed language, but as of version 4.0 is gradually typed, allowing variables to be explicitly marked as dynamic by using the `dynamic` type.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Raku (formerly Perl6) has had gradual typing implemented from the start.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Type checks occur at all locations where values are assigned or bound.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] An "untyped" variable or parameter is typed as `Any`, which will match (almost) all values.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The compiler flags type-checking conflicts at compile time if it can determine at compile time that they will never succeed.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Objective-C has gradual typing for object pointers with respect to method calls.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Static typing is used when a variable is typed as pointer to a certain class of object: when a method call is made to the variable, the compiler statically checks that the class is declared to support such a method, or it generates a warning or error.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] However, if a variable of the type `id` is used, the compiler will allow any method to be called on it.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] The JS++ programming language, released in 2011, is a superset of JavaScript (dynamically typed) with a gradual type system that is sound for ECMAScript and DOM API corner cases.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] GDScript, the Godot game engine's primary scripting language, started out dynamically typed and introduced gradual typing with version 3.1 of the engine, allowing users to type variables, function parameters, arrays and dictionaries through type hints.
[src:gradual-typing/gradual-typing] Additionally, when assigning a value to a variable using the `:=` notation, Godot will attempt to infer the type of the variable at build time.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In computer science, **type safety** is the extent to which a programming language discourages or prevents type errors.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Type-safe languages are sometimes also called **strongly** or **strictly typed**.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The behaviors classified as type errors by a given programming language are usually those that result from attempts to perform operations on values that are not of the appropriate data type, e.g. trying to add a string to an integer.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Type enforcement can be static (catching potential errors at compile time), dynamic (associating type information with values at run-time and consulting them as needed to detect imminent errors), or a combination of both.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Dynamic type enforcement can often run programs that would be invalid under static enforcement, but at the cost of introducing errors at runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In the context of static (compile-time) type systems, type safety usually involves (among other things) a guarantee that the eventual value of any expression will be a legitimate member of that expression's static type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The precise requirement is more subtle than this — see, for example, subtyping and polymorphism for complications.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In other words, if a type system is *sound*, then expressions accepted by that type system must evaluate to a value of the appropriate type (rather than produce a value of some other, unrelated type or crash with a type error).
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] A language is type-safe if the only operations that can be performed on data in the language are those sanctioned by the type of the data.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, what precisely it means for a program to be "well typed" or to "go wrong" are properties of its static and dynamic semantics, which are specific to each programming language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Consequently, a precise, formal definition of type soundness depends upon the style of formal semantics used to specify a language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In 1994, Andrew Wright and Matthias Felleisen formulated what has become the standard definition and proof technique for type safety in languages defined by operational semantics, which is closest to the notion of type safety as understood by most programmers.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] or can be reduced towards a value in some well-defined way.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In other words, the program never gets into an undefined state where no further transitions are possible.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] A number of other formal treatments of type soundness have also been published in terms of denotational semantics and structural operational semantics.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In isolation, type soundness is a relatively weak property, as it essentially just states that the rules of a type system are internally consistent and cannot be subverted.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Type safety is usually a requirement for any toy language (i.e., esoteric language) proposed in academic programming language research.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, many languages are too big for human-generated type safety proofs, as they often require checking thousands of cases.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Nevertheless, some languages such as Standard ML, which has rigorously defined semantics, have been proved to meet one definition of type safety.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Regardless of the properties of the language definition, certain errors may occur at run-time due to bugs in the implementation, or in linked libraries written in other languages; such errors could render a given implementation type unsafe in certain circumstances.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] An early version of Sun's Java virtual machine was vulnerable to this sort of problem.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Programming languages are often colloquially classified as strongly typed or weakly typed (also loosely typed) to refer to certain aspects of type safety.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Type safety is closely linked to memory safety.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Conversely, if the language is memory-safe, it cannot allow an arbitrary integer to be used as a pointer, hence there must be a separate pointer or reference type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] As a minimal condition, a type-safe language must not allow dangling pointers across allocations of different types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] But most languages enforce the proper use of abstract data types defined by programmers even when this is not strictly necessary for memory safety or for the prevention of any kind of catastrophic failure.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Allocations are given a type describing its contents, and this type is fixed for the duration of the allocation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] This allows type-based alias analysis to infer that allocations of different types are distinct.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Most type-safe languages use garbage collection.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Pierce says, "it is extremely difficult to achieve type safety in the presence of an explicit deallocation operation", due to the dangling pointer problem.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However Rust is generally considered type-safe and uses a borrow checker to achieve memory safety, instead of garbage collection.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In object-oriented languages type safety is usually intrinsic in the fact that a type system is in place.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] This is expressed in terms of class definitions.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] A class essentially defines the structure of the objects derived from it and an API as a *contract* for handling these objects.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Each time a new object is created it will *comply* with that contract.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Each function that exchanges objects derived from a specific class, or implementing a specific interface, will adhere to that contract: hence in that function the operations permitted on that object will be only those defined by the methods of the class the object implements.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] This will guarantee that the object integrity will be preserved.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Exceptions to this are object oriented languages that allow dynamic modification of the object structure, or the use of reflection to modify the content of an object to overcome the constraints imposed by the class methods definitions.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Ada was designed to be suitable for embedded systems, device drivers and other forms of system programming, but also to encourage type-safe programming.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] To resolve these conflicting goals, Ada confines type-unsafety to a certain set of special constructs whose names usually begin with the string Unchecked_.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Unchecked_Deallocation can be effectively banned from a unit of Ada text by applying pragma Pure to this unit.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] It is expected that programmers will use Unchecked_ constructs very carefully and only when necessary; programs that do not use them are type-safe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The SPARK programming language is a subset of Ada eliminating all its potential ambiguities and insecurities while at the same time adding statically checked contracts to the language features available.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] SPARK avoids the issues with dangling pointers by disallowing allocation at run time entirely.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Ada2012 adds statically checked contracts to the language itself (in form of pre-, and post-conditions, as well as type invariants).
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The C programming language is type-safe in limited contexts; for example, a compile-time error is generated when an attempt is made to convert a pointer to one type of structure to a pointer to another type of structure, unless an explicit cast is used.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, a number of very common operations are non-type-safe; for example, the usual way to print an integer is something like `printf("%d", 12)`, where the `%d` tells `printf` at run-time to expect an integer argument.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In addition, C, like Ada, provides unspecified or undefined explicit conversions; and unlike in Ada, idioms that use these conversions are very common, and have helped to give C a type-unsafe reputation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] For example, the standard way to allocate memory on the heap is to invoke a memory allocation function, such as `malloc`, with an argument indicating how many bytes are required.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The function returns a void pointer (`void*`), which the calling code must explicitly or implicitly cast to the appropriate pointer type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Pre-standardized implementations of C required an explicit cast to do so, therefore for an allocation of some `struct Foo`, the code `Foo* foo = (struct Foo*)malloc(sizeof(struct Foo))` became the accepted practice.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] `malloc()` returns `void*` which does not need to be explicitly cast in C, but in C++ this casting is made mandatory for type safety.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] It has support for untyped pointers, but this must be accessed using the "unsafe" keyword which can be prohibited at the compiler level.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] It has inherent support for run-time cast validation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Casts can be validated by using the "as" keyword that will return a null reference if the cast is invalid, or by using a C-style cast that will throw an exception if the cast is invalid.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Undue reliance on the object type (from which all other types are derived) runs the risk of defeating the purpose of the C# type system.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] It is usually better practice to abandon object references in favour of generics, similar to templates in C++ and generics in Java.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The Java language is designed to enforce type safety.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Anything in Java *happens* inside an object and each object is an instance of a class.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] To implement the *type safety* enforcement, each object, before usage, needs to be allocated.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Java allows usage of primitive types but only inside properly allocated objects.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Sometimes a part of the type safety is implemented indirectly: e.g. the class BigDecimal represents a floating point number of arbitrary precision, but handles only numbers that can be expressed with a finite representation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The operation BigDecimal.divide() calculates a new object as the division of two numbers expressed as BigDecimal.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In this case if the division has no finite representation, as when one computes e.g.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] 1/3=0.33333..., the divide() method can raise an exception if no rounding mode is defined for the operation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Hence the library, rather than the language, guarantees that the object respects the contract implicit in the class definition.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Standard ML has rigorously defined semantics and is known to be type-safe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, some implementations, including Standard ML of New Jersey (SML/NJ), its syntactic variant Mythryl and MLton, provide libraries that offer unsafe operations.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] These facilities are often used in conjunction with those implementations' foreign function interfaces to interact with non-ML code (such as C libraries) that may require data laid out in specific ways.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Another example is the SML/NJ interactive toplevel itself, which must use unsafe operations to execute ML code entered by the user.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Modula-2 is a strongly-typed language with a design philosophy to require any unsafe facilities to be explicitly marked as unsafe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] This is achieved by "moving" such facilities into a built-in pseudo-library called SYSTEM from where they must be imported before they can be used.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The import thus makes it visible when such facilities are used.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Unfortunately, this was not consequently implemented in the original language report and its implementation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] There still remained unsafe facilities such as the type cast syntax and variant records (inherited from Pascal) that could be used without prior import.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The difficulty in moving these facilities into the SYSTEM pseudo-module was the lack of any identifier for the facility that could then be imported since only identifiers can be imported, but not syntax.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The ISO Modula-2 standard corrected this for the type cast facility by changing the type cast syntax into a function called CAST which has to be imported from pseudo-module SYSTEM.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, other unsafe facilities such as variant records remained available without any import from pseudo-module SYSTEM.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] A recent revision of the language applied the original design philosophy rigorously.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] First, pseudo-module SYSTEM was renamed to UNSAFE to make the unsafe nature of facilities imported from there more explicit.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Then all remaining unsafe facilities where either removed altogether (for example variant records) or moved to pseudo-module UNSAFE.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] For facilities where there is no identifier that could be imported, enabling identifiers were introduced.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In order to enable such a facility, its corresponding enabling identifier must be imported from pseudo-module UNSAFE.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] No unsafe facilities remain in the language that do not require import from UNSAFE.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Pascal has had a number of type safety requirements, some of which are kept in some compilers.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Where a Pascal compiler dictates "strict typing", two variables cannot be assigned to each other unless they are either compatible (such as conversion of integer to real) or assigned to the identical subtype.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] Under strict typing, a variable defined as TwoTypes is *not compatible* with DualTypes (because they are not identical, even though the components of that user defined type are identical) and an assignment of `T1 := D2;` is illegal.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] An assignment of `T1 := T2;` would be legal because the subtypes they are defined to *are* identical.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, an assignment such as `T1.Q := D1.Q;` would be legal.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In general, Common Lisp is a type-safe language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] A Common Lisp compiler is responsible for inserting dynamic checks for operations whose type safety cannot be proven statically.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] However, a programmer may indicate that a program should be compiled with a lower level of dynamic type-checking.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] A program compiled in such a mode cannot be considered type-safe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The following examples illustrates how C++ cast operators can break type safety when used incorrectly.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In this example, `reinterpret_cast` explicitly prevents the compiler from performing a safe conversion from integer to floating-point value.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] When the program runs it will output a garbage floating-point value.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The two child classes have members of different types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] When downcasting a parent class pointer to a child class pointer, then the resulting pointer may not point to a valid object of correct type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] In the example, this leads to garbage value being printed.
[src:gradual-typing/type-safety] The problem could have been avoided by replacing `static_cast` with `dynamic_cast` that throws an exception on invalid casts.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:gradual-typing/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:gradual-typing/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
